      <exercise number="x2" permid="NNy">
        <statement>
          <p permid="EWC">
            Consider the operation that gives the distance between two numbers on the number line.  In other words, define <m>\ast</m> on <m>\R</m> by <m>x \ast y = |x-y|</m>.  Analyze this operation.  That is, decide whether the operation is associative, commutative, has an identity, and has inverses.  Is <m>(\R, \ast)</m> a group?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="dGq">
          <p permid="LRh">
            Yes, the operation is commutative, since <m>|x-y| = |y-x|</m>.  The operation is not associative though: <m>(2\ast 1)\ast 3 = ||2-1| - 3| = |1-3| = 2</m> but <m>2 \ast (1 \ast 3) = |2- |1-3|| = |2-2| = 0</m>.  This is enough to prove that <m>(\R, \ast)</m> is not a group.
          </p>

          <p permid="rYq">
            Even more, there is not an identity element: while 0 would be the natural choice here, and indeed <m>a \ast 0 = |a-0| = a</m> is true for all positive <m>a</m>, it is not true for negative <m>a</m>.  Since there is no identity, there can be no inverses.
          </p>
        </solution>
