      <exercise number="x5" permid="GiZ">
        <statement>
          <p permid="xsd">
            Define <m>\ast</m> on the real numbers <m>\R</m> by <m>x\ast y = x+y-5</m>.  Is <m>(\R, \ast)</m> a group?  Is it an abelian group?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="pUI">
          <p permid="Yfz">
            We will see that it is indeed an abelian group.  First, check that <m>\ast</m> is associative:
            <me permid="IBc">
              (x\ast y)\ast z = (x+y-5)\ast z = (x+y-5)+z - 5 = x+y+z - 10
            </me>.
            <me permid="oIl">
              x\ast (y \ast z) = x \ast (y+z-5) = x+(y+z-5)-5 = x+y+z - 10
            </me>.
            So <m>(x\ast y)\ast z = x \ast (y \ast z)</m> and the operation is associative.
          </p>
          <p permid="EmI">
            What about the identity?  We need to find a real number <m>e</m> such that <m>x \ast e = x</m>.  But <m>x \ast e = x+e-5</m>, and for this to be <m>x</m> it must be that <m>e = 5</m>.  We must also have <m>e \ast x = x</m> and indeed <m>5 \ast x = 5+x-5 = x</m>.  Thus there is an identity element, <m>e = 5</m>.
          </p>
          <p permid="ktR">
            For inverses, we much verify that for each <m>x \in \R</m> there is some other element <m>x' \in \R</m> such that <m>x \ast x' = x' \ast x = 5</m> (since <m>5</m> is the identity).  How can <m>x \ast x' = 5</m>?  Well <m>x \ast x' = x + x' - 5 = 5</m> means that <m>x' = 10 - x</m>.  And notice that <m>(10-x) \ast x = 10 - x + x -5 = 5</m> as needed.
          </p>
          <p permid="QBa">
            Thus <m>(\R, \ast)</m> does form a group.  It is also easy to check that <m>\ast</m> is commutative, so this is in fact an <em>abelian</em> group.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
