    <exercises xml:id="practice-gp-prop" permid="wPn">
      <title>Practice Problems</title>
      <exercise permid="Sxr">
        <statement>
          <p permid="JGv">
      Consider a group <m>G</m> which contains elements <m>a</m>,            <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>, with identity <m>e</m> (among others, possibly).  Solve each of the equations below for <m>x</m>.
            <ol permid="FNA">
              <li permid="vov">
                <m>axb=c</m>
              </li>
              <li permid="bvE">
                <m>x^2a = bxc\inv</m> given <m>acx=xac</m>.
              </li>
              <li permid="HCN">
                <m>x^2 = a^2</m> given <m>x^5 = e</m>.
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Cja">
          <p permid="wIj">
            <ol permid="BdH">
              <li permid="nJW">
                <p permid="PRg">
                  <m>x =  a\inv c b\inv</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="TRf">
                <p permid="vYp">
                  <m>x = bc\inv a\inv</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="zYo">
                <p permid="cfy">
                  <m>x = a^6</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="yEA">
        <statement>
          <p permid="pNE">
        For each of the following rules, either prove that it is true in every group <m>G</m> or give a counterexample.
            <ol permid="lUJ">
              <li permid="gfx">
                <p permid="ImH">
              If <m>x^2 = e</m>, then <m>x=e</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="MmG">
                <p permid="otQ">
                  <m>(ab)^2 = a^2b^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="stP">
                <p permid="UAZ">
              If <m>x^2 = x</m> then <m>x = e</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="YAY">
                <p permid="AIi">
              For every <m>x \in G</m>, there is some <m>y\in G</m> such taht <m>x = y^2</m> (in other words, every <m>x</m> has a square root).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="iqj">
          <p permid="cPs">
            <ol permid="hkQ">
              <li permid="EIh">
                <p permid="gPr">
              False.  Look at <m>D_4</m> for a counterexample. 
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="kPq">
                <p permid="MWA">
              False.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="QWz">
                <p permid="tdJ">
              True.  If <m>x^2 = x</m>, then <m>x^2x\inv = x x\inv</m> which simplifies to <m>x = e</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="xdI">
                <p permid="ZkS">
              False.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="eLJ">
        <statement>
          <p permid="VUN">
        If <m>a,b \in G</m> and <m>ab = ba</m>, we say that <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>
            <term>commute</term>.  Assuming that <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> commute, prove the following.
            <ol permid="SbS">
              <li permid="dkR">
                <p permid="Fsb">
                  <m>a\inv</m> and <m>b\inv</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="Jsa">
                <p permid="lzk">
                  <m>a</m> and <m>b\inv</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="pzj">
                <p permid="RGt">
                  <m>a</m> commutes with <m>ab</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="VGs">
                <p permid="xNC">
                  <m>a^2</m> commutes with <m>b^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="BNB">
                <p permid="dUL">
                  <m>xax\inv</m> commutes with <m>xbx\inv</m> for any <m>x \in G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Oxs">
          <p permid="IWB">
            <ol permid="NrZ">
              <li permid="hUK">
                <p permid="KbU">
              We know that <m>a\inv b\inv = (ba)\inv</m>.  But because <m>ab = ba</m>, we get that <m>(ba)\inv = (ab)\inv = b\inv a\inv</m>.  Thus <m>a\inv b\inv = b\inv a\inv</m>, which says that <m>a\inv</m> and <m>b\inv</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="ObT">
                <p permid="qjd">
              Note that <m>a = abb\inv</m>.  Since <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> commute, we get <m>a = bab\inv</m>.  Multiply by <m>b\inv</m> on the left: <m>b\inv a = a b\inv</m>, which is to say that <m>a</m> and <m>b\inv</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="ujc">
                <p permid="Wqm">
              We want to show that <m>a(ab) = (ab)a</m>.  Well, <m>a(ab) = a(ba)</m> since <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> commute, and <m>a(ba) = (ab)a</m> since the group is associative.  Therefore <m>a</m> and <m>ab</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="aql">
                <p permid="Cxv">
              Suppose <m>ab = ba</m>.  Now consider <m>a^2 b^2 = aabb</m>.  Since <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> commute, we have
                  <md permid="hdM">
                    <mrow>a^2b^2 \amp = aabb </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = abab </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = baab </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = baba = b^2a^2</mrow>
                  </md>

                Thus <m>a^2</m> and <m>b^2</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="Gxu">
                <p permid="iEE">
              We want to show that <m>(xax\inv)(xbx\inv) = (xbx\inv)(xax\inv)</m>.  Well the left hand side can be simplified:
                  <me permid="UPu">(xax\inv)(xbx\inv) = xabx\inv</me>
              and the right hand side can be simplified:
                  <me permid="AWD">(xbx\inv)(xax\inv) = xbax\inv</me>
              But since <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> commute, <m>xabx\inv = xbax\inv</m> so <m>xax\inv</m> and <m>xbx\inv</m> commute.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="KSS">
        <statement>
          <p permid="CbW">
        Let <m>G</m> be a group.  Let <m>a, b, c</m> denote elements of <m>G</m>, and let <m>e</m> be the identity in <m>G</m>.
            <ol permid="yjb">
              <li permid="mED">
                <p permid="OLN">
              Prove that if <m>ab = e</m>, then <m>ba = e</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="SLM">
                <p permid="uSW">
              Prove that if <m>abc = e</m>, then <m>cab = e</m> and <m>bca = e</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="uEB">
          <p permid="pdK">
            <ol permid="tzi">
              <li permid="ySV">
                <p permid="baf">
              Assume <m>ab = e</m>.  Then <m>a = b\inv</m>, so <m>ba = bb\inv</m>, or <m>ba = e</m>, as desired.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="fae">
                <p permid="Hho">
              Note that since <m>(ab)c = e</m>, we have that <m>ab = c\inv</m>.  That means that <m>c(ab) = e</m> as well.  Repeat for <m>a(bc) = e</m> to get the other equation.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="rab">
        <statement>
          <p permid="ijf">
        Prove that if <m>xay = a\inv</m>, then <m>yax = a\inv</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="aLK">
          <p permid="VkT">
        Suppose <m>xay = a\inv</m>.  Then <m>xaya = e</m>.  By the previous problem this means that <m>ayax = e</m> and also that <m>yaxa = e</m>.  But then multiply by <m>a\inv</m> on the right: <m>yax = a\inv</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="Xhk">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Oqo">
        Let <m>a</m>,            <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> each be equal to its own inverse.  Prove that if <m>ab = c</m>, then <m>bc = a</m> and <m>ca = b</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="GST">
          <p permid="Bsc">
        Suppose <m>ab = c</m>.  Then <m>abc = e</m> (since <m>c\inv = c</m>), so <m>bc = a</m> (multiply by <m>a</m> on the left of both sides). Also, <m>cab = e</m>, so <m>ca = b</m> (multiplying by <m>b</m> on the right of both sides).
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="Dot">
        <statement>
          <p permid="uxx">
        Prove that if <m>abc</m> is its own inverse, then <m>bca</m> is its own inverse, and <m>cab</m> is its own inverse.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="nac">
          <p permid="hzl">
        We are given that <m>abcabc = e</m>  We get that <m>bcabca = e</m> and <m>cabcab = e</m>, which is basically what we want to show (just group them appropriately).
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="jvC">
        <statement>
          <p permid="aEG">
        Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> each be equal to its own inverse.  Prove that <m>ba</m> is the inverse of <m>ab</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Thl">
          <p permid="NGu">
        We want to show that <m>(ab)(ba) = e</m>.  But <m>bb = e</m> and <m>aa = e</m>, so <m>abba = aa = e</m>, as required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>


    </exercises>


