      <exercise permid="AtN">
        <statement>
          <p permid="rCR">
          Let <m>G = (\R, +)</m>, the real numbers under addition.  Let <m>H = \{\log a \st a \in \Q,~ a \gt 0\}</m>.  Prove that <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="DYn">
          <p permid="tND">
          The identity of <m>G</m> is <m>0</m>, and <m>0 = \log 1</m>.  Since <m>1 \in \Q</m> and positive, we see that <m>0 \in H</m>. 
          </p>
          <p permid="ZUM">
          Suppose <m>a, b \in H</m>.  This means that <m>a = \log x</m> and <m>b = \log y</m> for some <m>x,y \in \Q</m>, both positive.  What about <m>a+b</m>?  Well, <m>a+b = \log x + \log y = \log(xy)</m>.  We have <m>xy \in \Q</m> and positive, so <m>a+b \in H</m>.
          </p>
          <p permid="GbV">
          Finall, for inverses, suppose <m>a \in H</m>.  Then <m>a = \log x</m> for positive <m>x \in \Q</m>.  The inverse will be <m>-a = -\log x = \log(x\inv)</m>.  But <m>x\inv \in \Q</m> and still positive, so <m>-a \in H</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="gAW">
        <statement>
          <p permid="XKa">
          Consider the group <m>G = (\R \times \R, +)</m>, the set of all ordered pairs of real numbers, under addition (where we add each coordinate independently: <m>(a,b) + (c,d) = (a+c, b+d)</m>).  Define the set <m>H = \{(x,y) \st y = 2x\}</m>.  Is <m>H</m> a subgroup of <m>G</m>?  Prove your answer.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="kfw">
          <p permid="nYr">
          Yes, <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.  For closure under addition, consider <m>(x_1, y_1) \in H</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2) \in H</m>.  This means that <m>y_1 = 2x_1</m> and <m>y_2 = 2x_2</m>.  What about <m>(x_1+x_2, y_1+y_2)</m>?  Well, <m>y_1+y_2 = 2x_1 + 2x_2 = 2(x_1+x_2)</m>, so indeed, <m>(x_1+x_2, y_1+y_2) \in H</m>.  
          </p>
          <p permid="UfA">
          For inverse, we need to check that <m>(-x, -y) \in H</m> given that <m>(x,y) \in H</m>.  Do it!
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="MIf">
        <statement>
          <p permid="DRj">
          Again consider <m>G = (\R\times \R, +)</m>, but this time define <m>H = \{(x,y) \st x^2 + y^2 > 0\}</m>.  Is <m>H</m> a subgroup of <m>G</m>?  Prove your answer.
